# Introduction

**dssoca** is a token-driven [Svelte 5](https://svelte.dev) design system: signal green on
near-black, monospace-forward, and **zero border-radius** everywhere. It is one global stylesheet
(`theme.css`) plus a small set of components — the building blocks of the `hubssoca` homelab UI,
extracted to stand on their own.

## The two axes

Everything is configured along **two orthogonal axes**, each written as a `data-*` attribute on an
ancestor element (usually `<html>`). Flip an axis and every component below it responds, because the
components only read CSS custom properties that the axes redefine.

| Axis      | Attribute            | Values              | Default |
| --------- | -------------------- | ------------------- | ------- |
| **Color** | `data-theme`         | `dark` · `light`    | `dark`  |
| **Size**  | `data-size-variant`  | `sm` · `md` · `lg`  | `md`    |

The two axes are independent: any theme combines with any size. See
[Theming & config](/theming) for how to set them and [Tokens](/tokens) for the live values they
resolve to.

## Principles

- **Zero border-radius.** Every radius token is `0`. Square corners are part of the identity.
- **Token-driven.** Components never hardcode sizes or colors — they read `--ss-*` custom
  properties, so one attribute flip rescales or recolors the whole tree.
- **Scoped styling.** Each component carries its own styles; the global stylesheet holds only
  tokens, base element styles, and app-shell layout.
- **Per-instance overrides.** Most components take a `size` prop to opt a single instance out of the
  ambient size, without touching anything else.

## What's here

The library ships **23 components** — from primitives like
[Button](/components/button), [Badge](/components/badge), and [Input](/components/input) to
app-shell pieces like [Topbar](/components/topbar), [Sidebar](/components/sidebar), and
[LogStream](/components/log-stream). Browse them in the sidebar, or start with
[Installation](/installation).

> This site dogfoods dssoca for its own chrome and embeds the live
> [Storybook](http://localhost:6006) stories on each component page. That link is the
> **local-dev default** (`http://localhost:6006` — run `pnpm storybook` alongside
> `pnpm docs:dev`); a deployed docs site points the embeds at a deployed Storybook by
> setting the `VITE_STORYBOOK_URL` env var (on Vercel: an env var on the docs project —
> see the repo `README.md` → *Deployment* and `documentation/CLAUDE.md`).
